c Language in the Writings of Baldassarre Loyola Mandes S.J. (1631–1667). Between Islamic Reminiscence and Catholic Controversy -- tPraxis conuertendi Mahumetanos. Tirso González de Santalla’s Manuductio -- t5 Ludovico Marracci -- tA Harmony of Intent: Bishop Gregorio Barbarigo (1625–1697) and Ludovico Marracci (1612–1700) -- tThe Role of Greek and Latin Auctores in Ludovico Marracci’s Alcorani Textus Universus -- tFrom dīn, milla, umma to religio, secta, superstitio: Marracci’s Latin-Arabic for “Religion” – A Lexical Analysis within the Historical Framework of the European History of the Modern Concept of Religion -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite its relevance to the subsequent development of Western Islamic studies, the intellectual contribution of early modern Catholicism is still an under-researched area. The aim of this volume is to fill this gap, offering a series of essays dealing with the study of the Qur’an and Arabic language in early modern Catholic Europe. Focusing on the circulation of manuscripts, translations and printed books, the essays highlight how Catholic Orientalism contributed to the birth and spread of Western Islamic studies, although sometimes it was still directed towards religious polemics. Among the protagonists of this period of Islamic studies, the volume will focus on Catholic priests, missionaries, religious orders (Jesuits, Franciscans, Carmelites) Eastern Christians, converts, and other prominent figures in the Catholic culture of the time. Special attention will be given to the work of Ludovico Marracci, author of a fundamental edition of the Arabic text and Latin translation of the Qur’an with an introduction, notes, refutations and religious and linguistic insights. The volume is of interest to an audience of specialists and non-specialists interested both in Islamic and Qur'anic studies and in the history of modern Catholicism, missions, and Orientalism  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aRELIGION / Islam / Koran & Sacred Writings.2bisacsh  aArabic language.  aEarly Modern Catholicism.  aOrientalism.  aQur'an.1 aArias-Torres, Juan Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanton, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCecini, Ulisse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFani, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoop, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartini, Giovanni Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcInally, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrolini, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrone, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPintimalli, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrado Garcia, Javier de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalierno, Loriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScotto, Davide, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShore, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStella, Federico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStella, Federico, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTottoli, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTottoli, Roberto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVázquez Ruiz, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r